<html xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">
 <head>
  <title>CSS Test: string set start-element can be an absolute</title>
  <link rel="author" title="Mike Bremford" href="http://bfo.com" />
  <link rel="help" href="https://drafts.csswg.org/css-gcpm-3/#using-named-strings" />
  <link rel="match" href="reference/string-set-013-ref.xht" />
  <meta name="flags" content="paged" />
  <meta name="assert" content="The first element on the page can not be an absolute" />
  <style>
  /* In this test the "set" element is an absolute. It is the first item opened on page
   * two in document order, but obviously as an absolute it can go anywhere, so it's
   * not the first visually.
   * Marking as "tentative" until the spec clarifies wht the definition of "first element
   * on the page" means in the case of absolutes.
   * See https://github.com/w3c/csswg-drafts/issues/4634
   */
  @page :first {
      @top-center {
          content: none;
      }
  }
  @page {
      margin: 72px;
      @top-center {
          content: "This should say pass: " string(foo, start);
      }
  }
  body {
      string-set: foo "FAIL";
  }
  img {
      width: 100%;
      height: 70vh;
  }
  .set {
      position: absolute;
      bottom: 0;
      string-set: foo "PASS";
  }
  </style>
 </head>
 <body>
  <p>This test has two pages. This page has no other content</p>
  <div>
   <img src="data:image/png;base64,iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUgAAAAEAAAABCAQAAAC1HAwCAAAAC0lEQVR42mP8/x8AAwMCAO+ip1sAAAAASUVORK5CYII=" />
   <div style="position: relative">
    <div class="set"></div>
    <img src="data:image/png;base64,iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUgAAAAEAAAABCAQAAAC1HAwCAAAAC0lEQVR42mP8/x8AAwMCAO+ip1sAAAAASUVORK5CYII=" />
   </div>
  </div>
 </body>
</html>
